e person behind the camera. In the context of digital imagery, however, these aesthetic strategies had the opposite effect, heightening the sense of realism by calling on tropes suggesting the authenticity to which viewers were accustomed. ILM’s style, on display in the most successful films of the 1980s and beyond, was so convincing that other studios were forced to follow suit, and today, ILM is a victim of its own success, having fostered a cinematic monoculture in which it is but one player among many.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCinematographyxSpecial effectsxHistory. 0aComputer animationxHistory. 0aDigital cinematographyxHistory. 0aMotion picture industryxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxAestheticsxHistory. 0aRealism in motion picturesxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aspecial effects, special effects in filmmaking, film production, cinematography, Star Wars franchise, Star Wars, film technology, blockbusters, Visual Effects.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076651640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32530840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477325315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477325315/original  a978-3-11-076651-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK